{{!--
  /freestyle/operators — compact, browseable index of the modifier vocabulary.

  Each transformation renders as a row in the same idiom as the trick dictionary
  and set encyclopedia (identity + type/ADD + set-only notation + status pill +
  click-throughs), grouped by movement-system axis. The Advanced Decomposition
  reference is retained below the index (shared sub-partial); a dedicated theory
  page is a later, separate decision.
--}}
<div class="hero hero-sm">
  <div>
    {{#if navigation.breadcrumbs}}
    <nav class="breadcrumb" aria-label="Breadcrumb">
      {{#each navigation.breadcrumbs}}
        {{#if href}}<a href="{{href}}">{{label}}</a> <span class="breadcrumb-sep">/</span> {{else}}<span>{{label}}</span>{{/if}}
      {{/each}}
    </nav>
    {{/if}}
    <h1>{{page.title}}</h1>
    {{#if page.intro}}<p class="hero-subtitle">{{page.intro}}</p>{{/if}}
  </div>
</div>

<div class="wrapper">
  <section class="content-section">
    <p>
      Operators are the movement ideas a player applies to a trick: a spin, a
      duck, a paradox layered onto a base. They are different from notation
      components such as <code>[PDX]</code> or <code>[XBD]</code>, which only
      record what happened and are listed separately at the foot of this page.
      Each row below is a compact directory entry: the operator's type, its ADD
      weight, and its status. Open <em>View details</em> for the full teaching
      page, or <em>Browse tricks</em> to see the tricks an operator produces. For
      set systems as first-class objects, see the
      <a href="/freestyle/sets">Set Encyclopedia</a>.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="content-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Established operators by structural role</h2>
    {{#each content.indexAxes}}
    {{#unless provisional}}
    <section class="operator-index-axis" id="axis-{{axisKey}}" aria-label="{{axisName}}">
      <h3 class="section-heading">{{axisName}}</h3>
      <div class="dict-trick-row-stack">
        {{#each modifiers}}
        <article class="dict-trick-row" id="operator-{{slug}}" data-modifier-slug="{{slug}}">
          <div class="dict-trick-row-head">
            <a class="dict-trick-row-title" href="/freestyle/modifier/{{slug}}">{{name}}</a>
            <span class="dict-trick-row-hashtag" aria-label="Tag identity">{{hashtag}}</span>
            <span class="operator-meta-chip">{{typeLabel}}</span>
            {{#if addLabel}}<span class="operator-meta-chip operator-meta-chip--add">{{addLabel}}</span>{{/if}}
            <span class="operator-status-pill operator-status-pill--{{status.key}}">{{status.label}}</span>
          </div>
          {{#if notation}}
          <div class="dict-trick-row-notation">
            <span class="dict-trick-row-job">
              <span class="dict-trick-row-label">SET</span>
              <code class="dict-trick-row-job-value">{{notation}}</code>
            </span>
          </div>
          {{/if}}
          {{#if descriptor}}<p class="operator-row-descriptor">{{descriptor}}</p>{{/if}}
          <p class="operator-row-links">
            <a class="operator-row-link" href="/freestyle/modifier/{{slug}}">View details &rarr;</a>
            <a class="operator-row-link" href="{{{browseHref}}}">Browse tricks &rarr;</a>
          </p>
        </article>
        {{/each}}
      </div>
    </section>
    {{/unless}}
    {{/each}}
  </section>

  <section class="content-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading" id="provisional-vocabulary">Provisional and historical vocabulary</h2>
    <p>
      These names are listed for completeness, but they are not ratified
      operators. Some have no settled definition yet; others have no teaching
      guide. Each row carries its own status so an unresolved name is never
      mistaken for an established operator.
    </p>
    {{#each content.indexAxes}}
    {{#if provisional}}
    <section class="operator-index-axis" id="axis-{{axisKey}}" aria-label="{{axisName}}">
      <div class="dict-trick-row-stack">
        {{#each modifiers}}
        <article class="dict-trick-row" id="operator-{{slug}}" data-modifier-slug="{{slug}}">
          <div class="dict-trick-row-head">
            <a class="dict-trick-row-title" href="/freestyle/modifier/{{slug}}">{{name}}</a>
            <span class="dict-trick-row-hashtag" aria-label="Tag identity">{{hashtag}}</span>
            <span class="operator-meta-chip">{{typeLabel}}</span>
            {{#if addLabel}}<span class="operator-meta-chip operator-meta-chip--add">{{addLabel}}</span>{{/if}}
            <span class="operator-status-pill operator-status-pill--{{status.key}}">{{status.label}}</span>
          </div>
          {{#if descriptor}}<p class="operator-row-descriptor">{{descriptor}}</p>{{/if}}
          <p class="operator-row-links">
            <a class="operator-row-link" href="/freestyle/modifier/{{slug}}">View details &rarr;</a>
            <a class="operator-row-link" href="{{{browseHref}}}">Browse tricks &rarr;</a>
          </p>
        </article>
        {{/each}}
      </div>
    </section>
    {{/if}}
    {{/each}}
  </section>

  <section class="content-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading" id="how-operators-combine">How operators combine</h2>
    <p>
      Compound operators expand into simpler ones: nuclear reads as paradox plus
      illusion, and blurry as stepping paradox. Furious is the canonical two-dex
      uptime set; barraging is a legacy name for it, not a separate set. Each
      operator&rsquo;s own decomposition and worked examples live on its detail
      page (open any row above).
    </p>
    <p id="alpine">
      Alpine is a folk name for a trick split into uptime and downtime by an
      inserted duck or dive; it is not a separate operator. For the movement it
      inserts, see the <a href="/freestyle/modifier/ducking">Ducking</a> and
      <a href="/freestyle/modifier/diving">Diving</a> pages.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="content-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading" id="notation-components">Notation components that are not operators</h2>
    <p>
      These record what happened during a trick. They are notation and scoring
      components, not operators a player applies. Their full definitions live in
      the glossary&rsquo;s Modifiers &amp; Operators section.
    </p>
    <ul>
      {{#each content.notationVocabulary}}
      <li><code>{{token}}</code>: {{meaning}}</li>
      {{/each}}
    </ul>
  </section>
</div>
